<br>
Note, though, that in terms of how normal civilian companies behave, deception in contracts is common, and hiding a clause or changes to a contract are standard practice. Remember, when VI altered the EULA and did not highlight specific sections for us? How many people knew that the EULA changed? How many even have a clue what the change was? I sure as heck don't.<br>
<br>
Generally, point I was getting at, is that contracts, no matter how 'binding' they might be, do not give the contract holder and the contractee legal rights to bypass all current laws just because a contract was signed (or in our case, clicked). <br>
<br>
Whether or not scanning a harddrive for software to alert the parent company for banning violates any Online Privacy acts (and there are some out there for the US) is up for debate. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tenesu>Tenesu</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#333333>(11/2/02 12:45:19 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=7687.topic&index=78>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_lightbulb.gif" align=absmiddle>  --</span><hr size=1> &quot;You can run, you can hide, but in the end you still need to listen on the ports. That you can't hide&quot;<br>
<br>
You may need to listen to ports, but you dont need to do it on the machine that EQ is running on.  If you use a hub, you can simply split the traffic among all the computers on the hub.  Then, if you're truely worried, just cut the tx line in your ethernet cable so the seq machine cant send anything back.  Seq still works, and invisibly. <br>
<br>
The problem now is that verant has started compressing data along with encrypting it.  In the past, data has not been compressed.  This makes it impossible to decrypt because compressing data means that the data looks pretty much like garbage.  The reason the devs of seq were able to decrypt the packets in the first place was because they knew what they should have looked like.  Now they cant run comparisons because the packets dont look like anything else.  Therefore, they would have to break a 64 bit key to get to the data, which is not going to happen.  <br>
<br>
However, this is still a problem for verant simply because to do the decrypting, the key for the crypto must be stored somewhere in ram on the eq machine.  Therefore, to break the crypto, you need to grab the key from ram, drop it to your seq box (in a variety of methods), and then use that key to decode the packets.  Once decoded, decompress them and seq works again.  <br>
<br>
The main crux of the situation is whether verant has legal rights to scan your computer.  This is still a hazy area with most people saying that, no, they cant, not legally.  Even if included in the EULA the search would not be legal as they would be violating your privacy rights along with some legaslation passed recently.  However, this may be a moot point in any case as it is still possible to hide programs in windows if you know how to do it.  And once they key is grabbed, the program may shut down as its job is done.  <br>
<br>
The main reason (we assume) that seq has been allowed to work for so long is because verant and seq had a gentlemans agreement.  Seq would never go to a windows version (and hence keep the number of users of seq to a minimum) and verant would not implement an unsolvable encryption method.  Now, verant has broken this assumed agreement and thats what has pissed off the seq devs.  Therefore, since they cant fix the problem now, they've decided to break their side of the agument by making a windows version.  (Seq has always been open source except for the decrypt library).  This will undoubtadly cause much more people to start using seq.  This leaves verant with a problem, they can either ban all the users using seq and take a user hit (and monetary hit therefore) or simply do nothing.  Depending on what they've chosen to do, this may put them between a rock and a hard spot.  As I am not a verant employee I dont know what they're going to do.  <br>
<br>
Also, before you start bitching about seq, perhaps you should read about the other side of the argument at the seq website at <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://seq.sourceforge.net">seq.sourceforge.net</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END-->  It never hurts to get another prespective.  Also, the devs were not doing this for money, or fame, or anything like that. They were doing it for fun and had 3 years of their work stripped away.   They had kept it as a linux version specifically to keep verant happy and out of their way but now it doesnt mean anything.  Oh well, I highly recomend you go read the posts on those boards.<br>
_Tenesu<br>
