<br>
*****<br>
I don't think the military (represented by the term 'Soldiers') really qualifies as a contract, and quite pointedly, anyone who signs up for the military generally has drilled into their head that this is dangerous, and death is easily possible.<br>
*****<br>
<br>
Bzzzzt.  Wrong again.  Joining the armed forces requires signing a contract, during the course of which you are obligated to follow the regulations of the branch of service, and ultimately, by oath, to defend the Constitution of the United States.  You will be jailed if you do not comply (and up until around 1943, you could conceivably be executed for failure to fulfill your obligations).  And no, generally having the possibility of death and danger is NOT &quot;drilled into their head&quot; until well after they have signed their contract and obligated themselves.  In many cases, persons serve career-length terms without having to face this possibility.<br>
<br>
*****<br>
Note, though, that in terms of how normal civilian companies behave, deception in contracts is common, and hiding a clause or changes to a contract are standard practice. Remember, when VI altered the EULA and did not highlight specific sections for us? How many people knew that the EULA changed? How many even have a clue what the change was? I sure as heck don't.<br>
*****<br>
<br>
What planet do you live on?  Every contract I ever wrote (which included several EULAs) were written with direct intent to be clear, concise, and with as little &quot;wiggle room&quot; for interpretation as possible.  You are sadly mistaken if you believe deception to be a &quot;common practice.&quot;<br>
<br>
*****<br>
Generally, point I was getting at, is that contracts, no matter how 'binding' they might be, do not give the contract holder and the contractee legal rights to bypass all current laws just because a contract was signed (or in our case, clicked). <br>
*****<br>
<br>
On this, I agree with you.  <br>
<br>
So will a judge, as the law of whatever locality/state/nation in which you live will out of course override contracts between individual entities where they conflict with one another (i.e., I can write a contract that says I own you in person and in perpetuity, and you might actually sign it, but no state in the union would uphold my &quot;right&quot; to enforce that contract, since slavery is deemed illegal by federal law).<br>
<br>
*****<br>
Whether or not scanning a harddrive for software to alert the parent company for banning violates any Online Privacy acts (and there are some out there for the US) is up for debate. <br>
*****<br>
<br>
I'm afraid you are mistaken again.  &quot;Acts&quot;, regardless of their existence, are not laws.  They count for about as much weight as navel lint until entered into law.  Currently, there are no Online Privacy laws, and the closest thing to it is the Hollings bill.  Take some time off from your perusal of this board, do a Google search on &quot;Hollings Bill&quot; find the content, of it, and read it.  You probably won't like some of what you read, but that's another thread entirely.<br>
<br>
Go back to grammar school, dude, or go out to Blockbuster and rent yourself a copy of &quot;Schoolhouse Rock&quot; and listen to &quot;I'm just a Bill&quot; over and over and over again until you understand this.<br>
<br>
You entered into a LICENSE AGREEMENT with VI when you purchased the media on which the software was recorded and installed it onto your machine.  Every time you activate that software, you affirm your agreement to the EULA as presented to you.  Any violation of that EULA is grounds for termination of the license agreement, with the effect of VI's denying you the use of their software.  By the same token, you may terminate that agreement at any time as well, by pressing &quot;I Decline&quot; and terminating payment.<br>
<br>
Get it through your skull.  This is a two-way agreement, not some grandiose case of constitutional law.  You are using this software under the conditions given.  If you don't like them, you have a choice of either terminating the agreement yourself, or operating outside of the terms, in which case VI will terminate the agreement if they catch you.<br>
<br>
